<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n50090f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n50" href="#n50090f">N50 (VI.B.37)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n50all.htm#n50090f"> 90(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> boars head</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">It is singular enough that even to the present day it is not only the custom in several parts of England to bring a garnished <mark>boar&apos;s head</mark> to table at Christmas, but that the descendants of the Northmen, in Yorkshire and the ancient Northumberland, do not even now neglect to place a large piece of wood on the fire on Christmas Eve, which is by some called the <i>yule-block</i>, by others <i>yule-clog</i>, or <i>yule-log</i> (perhaps from the old Scandinavian <i>l&aacute;g</i>, <i>log</i>, a felled tree; Norwegian, <i>laag</i>). Superstitious persons do not, however, allow the whole log to be consumed, but take it out of the fire again in order to preserve it until the following year. Exactly similar observances of Christmas customs still exist in the Scandinavian North. <small> J.J.A. Worsaae, <a name="JJAW2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JJAW2"><cite title="source">An Account of the Danes and Norwegians in England, Scotland and Ireland</cite></a> (1852) 83f</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
